</p><p>Factorials have been discovered in several ancient cultures, notably=
 in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_mathematics" title=3D"I=
ndian mathematics">Indian mathematics</a> in the canonical works of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jain_literature" title=3D"Jain literature=
">Jain literature</a>, and by Jewish mystics in the Talmudic book <i><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sefer_Yetzirah" title=3D"Sefer Yetzirah"=
>Sefer Yetzirah</a></i>. The factorial operation is encountered in many are=
as of mathematics, notably in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Comb=
inatorics" title=3D"Combinatorics">combinatorics</a>, where its most basic =
use counts the possible distinct <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
equence" title=3D"Sequence">sequences</a> =E2=80=93 the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Permutation" title=3D"Permutation">permutations</a> =
=E2=80=93 of <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span=
 class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: no=
ne;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displa=
