"></span>.</span> In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_=
analysis" title=3D"Mathematical analysis">mathematical analysis</a>, factor=
ials are used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_series" tit=
le=3D"Power series">power series</a> for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Exponential_function" title=3D"Exponential function">exponential=
 function</a> and other functions, and they also have applications in <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebra" title=3D"Algebra">algebra</a>,=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory" title=3D"Number th=
eory">number theory</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probabili=
ty_theory" title=3D"Probability theory">probability theory</a>, and <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_science" title=3D"Computer scien=
ce">computer science</a>.
</p><p>Much of the mathematics of the factorial function was developed begi=
nning in the late 18th and early 19th centuries.
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stirling%27s_approximation" title=
=3D"Stirling's approximation">Stirling's approximation</a> provides an accu=
rate approximation to the factorial of large numbers, showing that it grows=
 more quickly than <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponential_gro=
wth" title=3D"Exponential growth">exponential growth</a>. <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legendre%27s_formula" title=3D"Legendre's formula">=
Legendre's formula</a> describes the exponents of the prime numbers in a <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_factorization" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Prime factorization">prime factorization</a> of the factori=
als, and can be used to count the trailing zeros of the factorials. <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daniel_Bernoulli" title=3D"Daniel Bernoul=
li">Daniel Bernoulli</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonh=
ard_Euler" title=3D"Leonhard Euler">Leonhard Euler</a> <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interpolate" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Interpolat=
e">interpolated</a> the factorial function to a continuous function of <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number" title=3D"Complex numbe=
r">complex numbers</a>, except at the negative integers, the (offset) <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gamma_function" title=3D"Gamma function=
">gamma function</a>.
</p><p>Many other notable functions and number sequences are closely relate=
d to the factorials, including the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Binomial_coefficient" title=3D"Binomial coefficient">binomial coefficients=
</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Double_factorial" title=3D"D=
ouble factorial">double factorials</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Falling_factorial" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Falling factorial">=
falling factorials</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Primorial"=
 title=3D"Primorial">primorials</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Subfactorial" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Subfactorial">subfactor=
ials</a>. Implementations of the factorial function are commonly used as an=
 example of different <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_pro=
gramming" title=3D"Computer programming">computer programming</a> styles, a=
nd are included in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_calc=
ulator" title=3D"Scientific calculator">scientific calculators</a> and scie=
ntific computing software libraries. Although directly computing large fact=
orials using the product formula or recurrence is not efficient, faster alg=
orithms are known, matching to within a constant factor the time for fast <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplication_algorithm" title=3D"=
Multiplication algorithm">multiplication algorithms</a> for numbers with th=
e same number of digits.
</p>
