<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFactorial&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span><=
/a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The concept of factorials has arisen independently in many cultures:
</p>
<ul><li>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_mathematics" tit=
le=3D"Indian mathematics">Indian mathematics</a>, one of the earliest known=
 descriptions of factorials comes from the Anuyogadv=C4=81ra-s=C5=ABtra,<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-datta-singh_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factorial#cite_note-datta-singh-2"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> one of th=
e canonical works of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jain_literatu=
re" title=3D"Jain literature">Jain literature</a>, which has been assigned =
dates varying from 300 BCE to 400 CE.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factorial#cite_note-3"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></=
sup> It separates out the sorted and reversed order of a set of items from =
the other ("mixed") orders, evaluating the number of mixed orders by subtra=
cting two from the usual product formula for the factorial. The product rul=
e for permutations was also described by 6th-century CE Jain monk <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jinabhadra" title=3D"Jinabhadra">Jinabhad=
ra</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-datta-singh_2-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factorial#cite_note-datta-singh-2"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Hindu scholars have been using factorial formulas since at least 1150, whe=
n <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bh%C4%81skara_II" title=3D"Bh=C4=
=81skara II">Bh=C4=81skara II</a> mentioned factorials in his work <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/L%C4%ABl%C4%81vat%C4%AB" title=3D"L=C4=AB=
l=C4=81vat=C4=AB">L=C4=ABl=C4=81vat=C4=AB</a>, in connection with a problem=
