edia.org/wiki/Zeros_and_poles" title=3D"Zeros and poles">simple poles</a>. =
Correspondingly, this provides a definition for the factorial at all comple=
x numbers other than the negative integers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-borwein-corl=
ess_67-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fact=
orial#cite_note-borwein-corless-67"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>67=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
One property of the gamma function, distinguishing it from other continuous=
 interpolations of the factorials, is given by the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Bohr%E2%80%93Mollerup_theorem" title=3D"Bohr=E2=80=93Molle=
rup theorem">Bohr=E2=80=93Mollerup theorem</a>, which states that the gamma=
 function (offset by one) is the only <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Log-convex" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Log-convex">log-convex</a> f=
unction on the positive real numbers that interpolates the factorials and o=
beys the same functional equation. A related uniqueness theorem of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helmut_Wielandt" title=3D"Helmut Wielandt=
">Helmut Wielandt</a> states that the complex gamma function and its scalar=
 multiples are the only <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Holomorphi=
c_function" title=3D"Holomorphic function">holomorphic functions</a> on the=
 positive complex half-plane that obey the functional equation and remain b=
ounded for complex numbers with real part between 1 and 2.<sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-68" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factori=
al#cite_note-68"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>68<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Other complex functions that interpolate the factorial values includ=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hadamard%27s_gamma_function" tit=
le=3D"Hadamard's gamma function">Hadamard's gamma function</a>, which is an=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entire_function" title=3D"Entire =
function">entire function</a> over all the complex numbers, including the n=
on-positive integers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-69" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factorial#cite_note-69"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>69<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-70" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Factorial#cite_note-70"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>70<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/P-adic_number" title=3D"P-adic number"><span class=3D"texhtml m=
var" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span>-adic numbers</a>, it is not poss=
ible to continuously interpolate the factorial function directly, because t=
he factorials of large integers (a dense subset of the <span class=3D"texht=
ml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span>-adics) converge to zero acco=
rding to Legendre's formula, forcing any continuous function that is close =
to their values to be zero everywhere. Instead, the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/P-adic_gamma_function" title=3D"P-adic gamma function"><s=
pan class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span>-adic gamma=
 function</a> provides a continuous interpolation of a modified form of the=
 factorial, omitting the factors in the factorial that are divisible by <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">p</span>.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-71" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
actorial#cite_note-71"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>71<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digamma_function" title=
=3D"Digamma function">digamma function</a> is the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Logarithmic_derivative" title=3D"Logarithmic derivative">lo=
garithmic derivative</a> of the gamma function. Just as the gamma function =
provides a continuous interpolation of the factorials, offset by one, the d=
igamma function provides a continuous interpolation of the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harmonic_number" title=3D"Harmonic number">harmoni=
c numbers</a>, offset by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euler=
%E2%80%93Mascheroni_constant" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Euler=E2=80=93=
Mascheroni constant">Euler=E2=80=93Mascheroni constant</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-72" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factor=
ial#cite_note-72"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>72<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
